Camille Auer wanted to fix her gender, was diagnosed with a mental illness, and now she's doing art on the theme - "Man should have a right to his own body"
Dozens of patient reports hang from the ceiling of the Academy of Fine Arts’ Project room gallery.
They all have Camille Auer's name on them.
The papers tell a long story of how outsiders have written down their interpretation of Auer and his identity.
They decided for him who he was.
“I wanted to share my personal medical history to make the violence of the process visible,” Auer says.
In the process, he refers to the gender change process.
It is often a years-long research period that involves meetings with psychologists, psychiatrists, nurses and doctors.
The process starts with a referral for the "gender identity disorder" diagnostic studies, which are carried out in Tampere and Helsinki.
In the case of Auer, the process began four years ago.
Before this, she had already used the estrogen she had ordered via the Internet and was already very advanced in her own repair process.
She felt that she was a woman, but according to Finnish law, a person must go through a correction process in order to be able to legally correct the gender.
The Translating Act (563/2002) obliges transgender people to be forced to sterilize in order to get the right gender, for example, in a population register centre and a passport.
Currently, every gender corrective is required to have a psychiatric diagnosis and proof of infertility.
People have the right to decide on their own body.
"This situation is intolerable and violates human rights," said Auer.
Trans law reform has been discussed in Finland for a long time.
The UN Human Rights Council has issued eight remarks on the law, and the European Court of Human Rights has a preliminary ruling that obliges the parties to the European Convention on Human Rights to respect their right to self-determination.
The previous Finnish government was preparing the amendment of the Act under the leadership of the then Minister of Social Affairs and Health, Susanne Huovinen.
Elections were fired and the Finns took up the government.
The change in the law is stuck again.
These are domestic political disputes that are not even related to this law.
"The government does not want to put it on the table because there are disagreements within the government about the amendment of the law," said Frank Johansson, Executive Director of Amnesty International Finland.
The front of the exhibition space is dominated by two large installations.
One of them consists of the packaging and instructions for use of the medicines that Auer is taking.
In the patient story installation, any visitor can read, for example, the interpretation of Auer by the transpol psychologist at Tampere University Hospital.
The psychologist met Camille Auer twice and based on these, she wrote a story that would define Auer's right to care and help.
The sense of reality is subject to disruption.
The subject’s self-concept appears to be fragmented in a borderline-level manner, and personality-related unstable traits are emphasized.
Auer did not recognize himself from these descriptions.
"It was a shock to hear that I was diagnosed with a mental illness," Auer says.
What was even more shocking was that Auer was not given sex-change treatment.
According to the medical staff, his resources were not sufficient to initiate the process.
He was denied his own identity.
Then, on February 11, 2015, Auer walked out of the meeting and kicked the transpol waiting lobby into the air.
Later that television produced a work of art called Monument for the Exclud, in which Auer reflected on his experience of power and its use.
“It’s crazy that anyone who is defined as a woman at birth can enlarge their breasts, but a diagnosis is needed to remove the breasts,” Auer says.
Your body is not yours if you feel that you are more than your sex at birth.
Unfortunately, Auer's experience is not the only one of its kind.
For many, the process of gender correction is more difficult for mental reasons than for purely medical operations.
The participants will meet dozens of people to whom they must justify their own existence and their right to their own sex experience.
“It’s crazy that people who need support and help are denied treatment on the grounds that they don’t have enough resources,” Auer says.
Many of the participants in the process have psychological symptoms behind them: depression, anxiety, potential experiences of bullying.
On this basis, the medical staff may prescribe that treatment cannot be initiated.
"Preventing access to care and help can put a person in an even worse situation than it was before the process began," Auer says.
Auer’s personal exhibition also deals with anxiety and thoughts about suicide.
In the text of the exhibition publication, Auer writes: "I have had suicidal thoughts throughout my adult life, and that is something that people usually find difficult to digest."
The depression has been treated with medication, and when Auer started taking hormones, I felt better.
She had finally been able to articulate the feelings that had existed since childhood and adolescence.
Why the wide chin didn’t seem to fit in my body and why the chest muscles had to be round instead of a flat chest.
The most important thing for Auer has been that there are people around him who can see him.
Being seen is a basic need.
"You have to justify yourself so much by talking, dressing, using voice and movements," he says.
Today, Auer feels she is already being seen, she exists as a woman.
At the beginning of the process, however, random comments from close people could hurt a lot.
What hurts the most is when close people have sexual intercourse.
“They should know and they know who I am, but they don’t agree or can’t internalize it,” he said.
However, not all transgender people need physical changes.
They do not suffer from body dysphoria, a condition in which the body or parts of the body can cause anxiety and even physical pain.
Without the use of hormones and a long research process, however, you cannot get an official confirmation of your own gender.
"There is no medical basis for these studies," Auer says.
And it's true.
In Denmark, for example, in June 2014, Parliament adopted a new procedure for the recognition of legal gender.
The new legislation is based on self-determination in relation to legal gender.
An adult applicant submits a written application for a new personal identification number, in which he/she says that he/she feels that he/she is of the other sex.
After the six-month reflection period, the applicant confirms his or her application in writing and the Ministry gives the applicant a new personal identification number.
This right to self-determination is also required in Finland, and this demand is also summed up in the Auer exhibition.
It has not been a therapeutic experience for the artist, but the exhibition is a political and artistic collection of works.
I want to believe that art still has weight and that it can bring about political change at a time when politicians have forgotten about human rights.
