Civil Rights Organization issues travel warning to Missouri
The National Afro-American Civil Rights Organization (NAACP) has issued a travel warning against Missouri, due to its discriminatory practices and racist attacks.
“NAACP’s Missouri travel announcement will come into force on August 28, 2017, and urges African-American travellers, visitors and locals to pay special attention and exercise extreme caution when traveling in a state that has recently witnessed a series of dubious racial incidents,” the organization said in a statement.
The recent law in Missouri makes it difficult to export discrimination cases to the courts, and the state's enforcement of laws disproportionately targets minorities, which, according to the NAACP, led to the issuing of a travel warning.
“People’s civil rights are being violated.
They will be stopped for their skin colour and beaten or killed," said Rod Chapel, chairman of the NAACP in Missouri, in a statement to the Kansas City Star.
"We've never heard of so many cases in such a short period of time."
The Missouri Travel Alert is the first U.S. state warning issued by the organization.
The organization cited examples of racist remarks against African-American students at the University of Missouri and the death of 28-year-old black Tory Sanders from Tennessee.
Sanders died in dubious circumstances earlier this year, driving through the state when his car ran out of fuel, and was arrested by the Missouri police, even though he was not charged with a crime.
A Missouri attorney general’s office said police were 75% more likely to arrest a black driver than a white driver.
"The purpose of the travel release is to urge people to be alert and warn their families, friends and co-workers about what could happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
“People need to prepare, for example, by bringing in money to pay bail or telling relatives they’re going to travel through the state.”
According to the FBI, Missouri had one hundred hate crimes in 2015, the sixteenth largest in the United States.
The travel warning is also a response to Missouri’s new law, which makes it harder for companies to sue for discrimination in housing and employment.
The ACLU, the organization that defends the civil rights guaranteed by the Constitution, recently issued travel warnings to Texas and Arizona after they passed immigration laws that oblige the police to arrest people for immigration offences. The organization says this increases racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department and affect other states, but recently they have been issued by NGOs in response to certain laws and developments in the United States.
