Facebook: Don’t run for public office if you can’t stand criticism
The father of our country knew what bad publicity was.
Americans loved George Washington, but the newspapers soon began to criticize him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
The criticism must have annoyed you.
But he did not silence his critics.
"If freedom of speech is removed, we may be led dumb and silent like sheep to be slaughtered," Washington said in 1783.
Which brings us to the governor of Maryland, Larry Hogan, who should learn from Washington.
Hogan’s staff has removed at least 450 comments from his official Facebook page and blocked their authors.
Hogan was sued by the U.S. Civil Rights League earlier this week.
His staff found the challenge unfounded, and the attitude was also understated online.
"What does it matter? This is just Facebook," many commented.
But it matters,
Especially in the case of Hogan.
Hogan is the remarkably popular Republican governor of the Democratic-dominated state.
He has the second highest ranking among 50 governors.
Hogan's not responsive to hotheads.
He has led the state steadfastly and firmly adhered to the principles.
He has also skillfully used Facebook as the main channel of communication with his constituents and published a photo of a bald head in chemotherapy.
Therefore, blocking users from coming to the governor's Facebook page is unnecessary and even dangerous. The governor's page is a public and official forum maintained by his staff with tax money.
Hogan's spokeswoman, Amelia Chasse, defended the governor's actions in an interview with the Washington Post, saying it was just a question of moderating comments.
However, stigmatizing commentators as trolls, spammers or haters is too easy.
The Washington Post interviewed Hogan on Facebook.
They turned out to be ordinary people who wanted to talk to leaders of their choice, not trolls, but teachers, entrepreneurs, pastors, for example.
They said their comments were respectful, thoughtful and appropriate.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his comment; he wanted to appeal to Hogan’s Catholic faith.
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Maryland Bowie was not hostile, but asked a question about hate crimes.
"I politely comment that I am disappointed that Hogan has not commented on the hate crimes and other recent news," he wrote in a Washington Post commentary.
“I also cannot accept that when more than one person comments on the same issue, they are immediately considered to be somehow organized and ignored as a large group of concerned citizens.”
The governor's staff called the comments a "focused attack." Someone else could call them to advance what they thought was important.
In the age of Facebook, it’s easy to manage communication by blocking a reviewer or deleting a critical comment.
In the old days, staff should have been sent to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials, or to arrest and silence demonstrators.
It’s the same thing now, just digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be accused of shackling Facebook and other social media channels.
Twitter users blocked by President Trump have sued him.
The first major decision was made last week in Virginia.
Alexandria District Court Judge James C. Cacheris said the Loudoun County Government violated the First Amendment of the United States Constitution by blocking a voter on Facebook.
And the U.S. Civil Liberties Union visited to discuss the use of Twitter and Facebook with Kentucky’s Republican Governor Matt Bevin.
This shouldn't be hard.
In Washington’s time, cheap postage had the same effect as the internet today.
The number of newspapers quadrupled from 1776 to 1800, and anonymous writers hammered Washington.
There were trolls then.
The nicknames Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius and Portius wrote letters to newspapers in which they scoffed at Washington's decisions.
The President's office was flooded with petitions criticising the Jay Agreement, the U.S.-UK Cooperation, Trade and Shipping Agreement, as documented by the Papers of George Washington network project.
However, he did not silence his critics.
Freedom of expression, freedom of opinion and freedom of discussion are the cornerstones of our nation.
True leadership means acknowledging this fact.
