Bardina Degei doesn't use a stove in her cooking.
He also rarely uses the pot.
Degei lives in a wooden building in Enarotal, the capital of the Paniai region, located in the turbulent Papua province of Indonesia. When he prepares dinner, he usually puts sweet potatoes – locally “take” – directly into the fireplace.
After half an hour, the sweet potato burned on the stubble is eaten greedily with bare, unwashed hands.
She sits on a muddy floor, where she usually also carries out her daily chores, such as washing in cloudy water from a nearby bog.
The toilet is provided by a bucket in the roofless room.
Degei is the youngest of her husband's four wives, and she is not assigned to care for fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous: most of the people in the village are unemployed, and many drink a lot.
"No one dares to walk around the village after 5 p.m.," Degei says.
This is a rare glimpse into everyday life in the Papua Highlands, a former Dutch colony annexed to Indonesia in 1969, preceded by a controversial referendum in which 1,026 village elders were forced to vote publicly in front of the occupying forces.
The local independence movement, which opposed Dutch rule, quickly turned its anger to the Jakarta government, which tightly controls the area and prevents foreign journalists and human rights observers from entering it.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and Western Papua, and the eastern part of the island belongs to Papua New Guinea.
The journey starts with a one and a half hour flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire and continues with a five-hour trip in a rental car.
There is no public transport here.
With a population of about 19,000, the city has wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, with corrosion on the corrugated roofs.
Few Indonesians have been here, not to mention journalists and foreigners.
Before the arrival of the Christian missionaries, the Papuan Mee Pago people worshiped the Uga Tamee god.
Other changes have taken place.
"We didn't have these clothes," Degei says. She means her colorful, hand-woven winding headdress, dark skirt and brightly colored blouse.
"Before we had only leaves to cover our bodies."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of the population living below the poverty line, with child mortality and illiteracy among the highest in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's gold country.
Paniai is about the size of New Jersey, with a population of 153,000. Just a hundred kilometers from Paniai is Grasberg, the largest and most profitable gold mine in the world. It is owned by Freeport McMoran, a company based in Phoenix, USA.
