In 2005, the New York Times revealed that Freeport paid local military personnel and local military units nearly <0x24>20 million between 1998 and 2004, with individual officers being paid up to <0x24>150,000.
Papua's demands for greater sovereignty threaten this source of income and are mercilessly silenced.
Human rights activists say the Indonesian army has killed, raped, tortured and imprisoned more than 500,000 Papuans since 1969.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, the massacres in the highlands of Papua tribes in the 1970s took proportions to genocide.
Last year, more than 3,900 people were arrested in peaceful demonstrations by the Indonesian police.
A 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, We Will Lose Everything, reports the atrocities of the previous year, including extrajudicial executions, torture – rape and electric shocks are particularly popular – and ruthless attacks on peaceful demonstrations.
"It's difficult to count the number of victims because there are cases every week," said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
Screws have been tightened as Papua’s natural resources attract migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
Of the 3.5 million inhabitants of the province, 83% are Christians, but the demographic is changing as Muslims from the Indonesian islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi move to the region in the hope of a better livelihood.
