They carried hunting bows for ceremonial ceremonies and began to perform the traditional waita dance of the Papuan Mee Pago tribe, dancing in circles and imitating bird songs.
Some protesters began stoning police and military buildings.
When the atmosphere got hotter, the soldiers were told on the internal radio system: "If crowds resist more than three times, shoot them to death." This information is based on an official document seen by TIME magazine, which has not been disclosed to the local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the resident leader of the Kego Koto district, felt the situation was getting out of hand and asked the crowd to calm down and return to their homes.
No one wanted to listen anymore.
"When I turned around, I was shot in my left wrist," he told TIME magazine on the porch of his wooden house painted in bright color.
Kayame still doesn't know who shot him, but the bullet came from the ranks of the soldiers.
"Several shots were fired in the crowd."
Alfius Youw was shot three times, and his cousin saw the shootings.
"I ran to him and made sure it was really him," Yohanes told TIME magazine, sadly. Like many Indonesians, he uses only one name.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
Yotje Mende, the chief police inspector in Papua, told reporters that the police were simply "protecting" the police station because it was under attack.
"We must defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us," Pudjo Sulistiyo, a spokesman for the Papua Police Department, said in 2015.
"Then it's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many were injured.
The news of the killing reached Jakarta the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave an emotional speech in Jayapura, in which he expressed his condolences to the families of the victims and promised that the violence in Papua would be addressed.
"I want the case to be investigated immediately so that nothing like this ever happens again."
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he would launch investigations into human rights violations outside the judicial system.
He immediately began to withdraw from his speech.
