In an interview with TIME magazine in Jakarta on 5 June 2017, Wiranto had already changed his mind. He said that he did not intend to start investigations in Papua.
"Everything will be clarified in court," he said.
The United Nations accuses Wiranto of "crimes against humanity" related to the deaths of more than 1,000 people in the bloody independence vote in East Timor in 1999. Wiranto told TIME that 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua have already been solved, including Paniai incidents.
The families of the Paniai victims are grimly distrustful of the allegations.
"I've been interviewed four times in the last three years, but things haven't progressed at all," Yohanes said.
"I'm tired of this."
He says he still lives in fear, even though it’s been years.
“Yes, I am afraid,” he says.
