The shootings have not stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired at villagers in the neighboring area of Paniai in Deiya.
One was killed and 17 were injured in a conflict between villagers and the head of a construction company, which began when the head refused to take the man who had lost his mind to the hospital, including children.
Ravianus Douw, a 24-year-old man who had been caught by the water while fishing on a nearby river, died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested at a construction site in front of the company's office.
Police said the villagers stoned police officers who responded with warning shots.
According to locals, however, the Indonesian paramilitary police’s mobile police unit opened fire on the crowd, killing one villager.
"We're terrified. We're afraid of revenge," says 29-year-old Dominggu Badii, who lives near the hospital and saw the wounded being brought in for treatment.
"I've been hiding at home for two days."
The Deiyai parliament has called for the shooting of police officers to be held accountable and for a mobile police unit to be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a problem for the Indonesian government.
The lack of real development fuels discontent among the Mee, Moni, Dani, and Damal tribes, who live in the lush mid-heavens of Papua.
Many have joined the Papuan Liberation Movement (OPM), an army of rebels who claim to defend the rights of the Papuans through occasional attacks and the kidnapping of Indonesian army soldiers.
Some of the OPM leaders are from Pania, such as Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
The army has responded to the insurrection by arbitrarily arresting and imprisoning thousands of people in Pania in the name of "safeguarding national sovereignty".
Some of the detainees will never return.
Among Papuas, Paniai is known as a "sad, forgotten place".
Poverty fuels dissatisfaction.
There's very little rice for sale in Enarotal, and that's too expensive for the locals.
Like the bread.
People grow their own food: mainly sweet potatoes and some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Cultivation is the work of women, and one woman can be responsible for four or five sweet potato fields.
Most of the crop is for the family, and the rest is sold at the market.
Ten sweet potatoes cost only 10,000 rupees (75 cents).
