The lack of freedom of the press means that the Indonesian government is under pressure only from its closest neighbours.
In March, six Pacific states – Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands – urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate Papua’s “numerous and widespread violations”, including the Paniai shooting scene.
These countries have traditionally also supported the Papua Liberation Movement.
The Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman, Arrmanatha Nasir, denied the allegations and told journalists in Jakarta that “Indonesia is still a democracy with freedom of the press, so it would be difficult to conceal evidence of human rights violations.”
The locals want foreign governments to intervene.
When an official Dutch delegation led by human rights ambassador Kees Van Barer visited Jayapura on 4 May 2017, the locals broke the silence and expressed their desire for freedom, an anonymous source said.
Indonesia's presidential election is 2019, but Papuas say they are no longer likely to vote for Jokow.
"Jokowi has good intentions, but there are people around him who are involved in the Paniai shooting scene," said Gobai, chairman of the Tribal Council.
He wants Jokow to know about the situation of the Panaeans: they live under the rule of a greedy and unpredictable army in poverty and want, practically without health care and education.
According to Gobai, the Panaeans, like other Papuans, consider their votes to be a "debt" to be repaid.
