New age test results for asylum seekers in Sweden announced
The latest results of medical age tests for asylum seekers in Sweden have been released. The results of tests carried out using the new assessment method reveal that more than 80% of those tested were found to be over 18 years of age. However, not everyone considers the tests to be reliable.
The Swedish National Forensic Medicine Agency began testing earlier this year.
The new test was introduced after the Swedish Immigration Service was criticised for failing to determine the real age of applicants claiming to be minors.
To date, the Finnish Immigration Service has commissioned 6,880 tests, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests, which were carried out between mid-March and the end of July 2017.
In addition, in 25 cases, the Forensic Medicine Agency determined that the test subject was ‘possibly 18 years of age or older’.
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the asylum seeker was "possibly under the age of 18".
Tests were carried out only in cases where there was reason to doubt the age stated by the applicant.
Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency says the results are consistent with the results of previous months.
"The figures are fairly consistent. There are no big differences between the statistics of the previous months," he told The Local.
Although a large number of applicants were determined to be over 18 years of age, this does not necessarily mean that applicants have lied about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases there were "indicatives that the subject is 18 years of age or older".
When Svenska Dagbladet looked at the same results, it turned out that in 243 cases, the applicant had openly stated that he would turn 18 this year.
In the medical age assessment method used for tests, X-rays of wisdom teeth and magnetic resonance imaging of knee joints are taken. Then the images are analyzed by dentists and radiologists. The method has also been criticized.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institutet, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of humans.
"I have had some reason to think about it and I think that the method used is not the right one.
The determination of biological age in this way is very uncertain.
"If we can't determine the age for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can do it," he told the Metro newspaper.
However, the forensic agency Göransson defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, it can be said that the risk of defining a child as an adult is low.
The risk is highest in a situation where the test subject is about to turn 18 years old, at which point the risk is about 10%."
