From September, patients can be prescribed a "revolutionary" anti-HIV drug. The Supreme Court closed a dispute over the financing of the drug in the public health system (NHS) in England.
The NHS reported that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is prescribed to approximately 10,000 people during the first three-year trial. Pre-intercourse medication has been found to reduce the risk of infection by approximately 86% in high-risk individuals.
The NHS agreed to fund the experiment after the Court of Appeal upheld last year’s Supreme Court ruling, stating that the NHS could pay for the PrEP, although it argued that it should be financed by the local authorities.
NHS chief Simon Stevens called the decision a “significant new intervention,” and the National AIDS Organization described it as “a crucial moment.”
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to accept enrolments for a trial that will expand to other clinics in October. The trial will reach its full reach in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an anti-HIV medicine taken before intercourse that reduces the risk of infection.
Experiments have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV infection in risk groups.
Taking the medicine before intercourse means that there are enough medicines in the body to prevent HIV infection during intercourse.
It can be taken daily or two hours before sex.
The target group of treatment includes gay men, bisexual men and transgender people, as well as people with HIV-positive partners who are not receiving effective treatment.
Clinics select eligible candidates from men, women, transgender people and those whose HIV-positive partner is not known to receive antiretroviral treatment for their disease.
People living in England and enrolled in a general practitioner can also apply for a trial at their local sexual health clinic.
The program costs <0xC2><0xA3>10 million, and this week the NHS of England signed a procurement contract for medicines after an international tender.
The purpose of the experiment is to assess the potential of PrEP by collecting extensive clinical evidence on its targeting, taking and treatment implementation.
“This major new intervention should complement and enhance the diverse and increasingly effective ways we already have to prevent HIV,” says Stevens.
“It’s another major achievement in over 30 years of fighting to solve one of humanity’s greatest health challenges.”
"This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV," said Deborah Gold, director of the National AIDS Organization.
“If PrEP is targeted correctly to those who need it and to those at risk, it can have a pivotal impact on the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, those at risk will receive a drug through an NHS-funded experiment, which they can decide on their own use without the need to consult a partner. This will have an empowering effect that will improve the lives of a huge number of people.
This is welcome news.”
"The most important thing now is to ensure that the experiment is launched quickly across the country and that no one at risk is left out," said Ian Green, director of the Terrence Higgins Foundation.
“The PrEP drug used in the trial has been acquired, and we will soon be able to protect ten thousand people at risk from HIV infection.”
"The start of the PrEP experiment is a welcome event that was unnecessarily delayed for several months due to the government's slowdown," Sharon Hodgson, the shadow government's health minister, said in a statement.
“We have evidence that the drug can have a pivotal impact on our work to prevent HIV and stop the spread of this threatening disease.
