When Ferrell drove towards Ferguson with his daughter dressed in a flower dress and a matching crown, they re-discussed what it was like to live in black and under what conditions.
"Remember when I told you how black people have had to fight for the things they believe in?" Ferrell remembers telling his daughter.
“We’re going to Ferguson because the police killed an 18-year-old boy, and that’s not right.”
"I couldn't stop taking my daughter with me," Ferrell said later.
"Today's events are...the culmination of past events.
My daughter has a right to know it and grow up in it.
He needs to be prepared for activism and organization, but he also needs to know the different layers and circumstances of the experience of living as a black person, and he needs to know what we need to do to be free, to be free ourselves.
Even though I’ve been able to protect her from blatant racism, she’s still just like the other black girls.
I feel like I would hurt him if I protected him from reality.”
Their first stop in Ferguson was South Florissant Road, opposite the police station, which became a camp for activists as they waited to be informed of the case and finally learned that no charges would be filed against the police.
From there, Ferrell and his daughter went to help a local entrepreneur who made lunch packages.
They packed lunches in bags and distributed them to the protesters.
Ferrell gradually began to take a new approach to activism.
"My activism completely changed after August 9," he says. While studying at the University of Missouri in St. Louis, Ferrell was chairman of the Association of Nursing Students from Minorities. At the time, he focused on food law and health inequalities in black communities.
“I had no experience of organizing.
