Folayan said that he and filmmaker Lucas Alvarado-Farrar “simply wanted to tell us what was going on.”
Ferrell was sneaked into suspicion and asked, "Do you really want to tell me what's going on, or do you want a story that you can use?"
The reason for the suspicion was the countless times that people, usually white people, had appeared in the local community, who only wanted to take advantage of its difficulties and perseverance.
"We had heard that those who were born and raised in Ferguson did not have a voice in common," Folayan said in an interview recently. "We wanted to do things differently."
Folayan had already contacted Deputy Director Damon Davis, who is known for his activism with prisoners sentenced to death.
Davis' involvement prompted Ferrell to join the project along with six other locals, and the shooting team followed the events in the years following Brown's shooting.
“This is not a documentary where someone speaks to us or speaks for us, but we speak,” Davis said.
“The most important thing for me was how the local people are portrayed in the movie because I’m being portrayed in the same way.”
According to Mr Folayan, the intention was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences, because it was to show that the popular movement "is not about a charismatic leader, but about the community".
That’s why the documentary shows surprisingly private aspects of Ferrell’s life, such as falling in love and getting married.
"I felt pretty naked," Ferrell laughs as he tells me how it felt to see the movie for the first time.
"But I understood that this work and the human description of blacks require a certain degree of vulnerability."
In addition, Ferrell’s story repeats and re-focuses the role of black queer women in the wider Black Lives Matter movement.
