Red meat, dairy products and chocolate may alleviate irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like digestive nightmares.
However, a recent study argues the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products may ease irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 people in the UK. It causes abdominal cramps, swelling, repeated or bloody diarrhoea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
People suffering from irritable bowel syndrome are generally advised to avoid meat and dairy products. However, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan in the protein helps the body develop immune cells that strengthen intestinal tolerance.
According to study leader Marco Colonna, the immune cells guard the bowels and make sure that no harmful microbes hidden in the food do not enter the body.
Cells that cause inflammation are balanced by cells that strengthen resistance. They protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance falls too close to inflammation, the result may be irritable bowel syndrome.
The experiments showed that immune cells that strengthen tolerance were found in mice that had a certain bacterium in their intestines.
Tryptophan is one of the building blocks of proteins, and it is essential for the development of immune cells.
"We found a link between Lactobacillus reuteri and the development of cells that promote tolerance. Lactobacillus reuteri is part of the normal intestinal microbiome," says Professor Colonna.
"The more tryptophan in the diet of mice, the more immune cells they had."
If the same works in humans, a combination of Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria and a diet rich in tryptophan can strengthen intestinal tolerance and reduce susceptibility to inflammation.
Researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barragan, a postdoctoral researcher on immune cells that strengthen immunity, found that although one group of mice had such cells, they did not have them in mice of the same species that were kept separate from the other group.
He suspected that the difference was related to the intestinal microbiome of mice, the normal community of bacteria, fungi and viruses in the digestive tract.
When examining the intestinal DNA of mice, six species of bacteria were found in mice with immune cells, but not in other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri was given to mice that grew up in a sterile environment and did not have a gut microbiome and did not develop immune cells, they started to develop immune cells.
The researchers wanted to find out how the bacteria affect the immune system. They grew Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in liquid and transferred small amounts of liquid —without the bacteria— to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells developed into resilience-enhancing cells.
When the active ingredient was cleared from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the number of cells that strengthened tolerance increased by about 50 percent. When the amount of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells fell by half from the previous one.
According to Cervantes-Barragan, humans have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as mice, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our digestive tract.
It is not yet known whether by-products of tryptophan from Lactobacillus reuteri cause cells to develop in humans in the same way as in mice. However, genetic defects related to tryptophan have been observed in people with IBS.
"We probably want to promote the development of such cells because they regulate the inflammation on the inner surfaces of the intestines," says Cervantes-Barragan.
"High levels of tryptophan combined with Lactobacillus reuteri may contribute to their proliferation."
